[[ja:車持部]] [[sn:Kuramochibe]] [[en:Kuramochibe]]
<!--Kuramochibe--><!--Kuramochibe--><!--Kuramochibe--> [[Category:車持氏]]

'''Kuramochibe''' (車持部, also pronounced Kurumamochibe) was one of the [[Bemin|Be groups]] in ancient Japan. They were responsible for the production and maintenance of imperial palanquins. The individuals who managed and supervised these tasks, often owning the associated land, were members of the [[Kuramochi clan]] (車持氏), specifically the Kuramochi no Kimi.
== History == According to the ''[[Nihon Shoki]]'' (Chronicles of Japan), in the 5th year of [[Emperor Richū]]'s reign, Kuramochi no Kimi appropriated the resources of the Kuramochibe in [[Tsukushi Province]] and seized the Kuramochibe allocated to the [[Munakata Shrine]]. As a punishment, the Kuramochibe in Tsukushi Province was confiscated.
== Provinces with Kuramochibe == Provinces where Kuramochibe were present, or are believed to have been present, include the following:<ref>Ōta Ryō, ''Seishi Kakei Jisho'' (Genealogical Dictionary of Surnames), Isobe Kōyōdō, 1920.</ref> * [[Yamato Province]] * [[Settsu Province]] (''[[Shinsen Shōjiroku]]'' records, "Kuramochi no Kimi, descendants of Toyokiiribiko no Mikoto.") * [[Iga Province]] (associated with Kuramochi no Omi) * [[Ise Province]] (associated with [[Kuruma Otoshigami Shrine|Kuruma Shrine]]) * [[Kazusa Province]] (''[[Wamyō Ruijushō]]'' mentions Kuramochi villages in Nagara District and Habu District. Kuramochi no Kimi is linked to the descendants of Isaza no Kimi.) * [[Shimōsa Province]] (Okada District had a Kuramochi village; an inscribed earthenware from the Ikenoshita archaeological site in [[Inzai]] City reads: "Kuramochi □...second year of the □ calendar.") * [[Hitachi Province]] (Makabe District contained a Kuramochi village.) * [[Ōmi Province]] (The 1st-year tax ledger for Shika District mentions Kuramochi no Kimi Shimasu○; in the 2nd year, listed as Kuramochi no Kimi Shimasu○.) * [[Kawachi Province]] * [[Harima Province]] * [[Tango Province]] * [[Kōzuke Province]] (Kuruma District in Gunma Prefecture was associated.) * [[Wakasa Province]] (Kuramochi village existed in Ōi District.) * [[Echizen Province]] * [[Etchū Province]] (Kuramochi District in Niikawa existed.) * [[Tsukushi Province]]
== Notes == {{Notelist}}
== References == {{Reflist}}
