'''Kuramochibe''' (車持部, also pronounced Kurumamochibe) was one of the {{ill|Bemin|en|Bemin|qid=Q2892644|lt=Be groups|1=Bemin}} in ancient Japan. They were responsible for the production and maintenance of imperial palanquins. The individuals who managed and supervised these tasks, often owning the associated land, were members of the [[Kuramochi clan]] (車持氏), specifically the Kuramochi no Kimi.

== History ==
According to the ''[[Nihon Shoki]]'' (Chronicles of Japan), in the 5th year of {{ill|Emperor Richū|en|Emperor Richū|qid=Q329704|lt=Emperor Richū|1=Emperor Richū}}'s reign, Kuramochi no Kimi appropriated the resources of the Kuramochibe in {{ill|Tsukushi Province|en|Tsukushi Province|qid=Q1206461|lt=Tsukushi Province|1=Tsukushi Province}} and seized the Kuramochibe allocated to the [[:en:Munakata Shrine|Munakata Shrine]]. As a punishment, the Kuramochibe in Tsukushi Province was confiscated.

== Provinces with Kuramochibe ==
Provinces where Kuramochibe were present, or are believed to have been present, include the following:<ref>Ōta Ryō, ''Seishi Kakei Jisho'' (Genealogical Dictionary of Surnames), Isobe Kōyōdō, 1920.</ref>
